The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Mobile makers pick growth drivers
                                                                                                               Mobile makers pick growth drivers
          JAYATI GHOSE                              
	New Delhi, March 10: Cellular phone makers are targeting the premium and entry-level markets.        
	This year will see the emergence of two distinct customer base, the basic voice phone user and the gizmo lover, Sunil Dutt, country head, Samsung Telecom told The Telegraph.        
	To improve access, firms are joining hands with microfinance companies in rural areas. Simultaneously, for the gizmo lover, they are offering mobiles with touch-screens, multimedia, high-speed Internet and huge data storage capacities.        
	The new (budget phone) Guru portfolio is being strengthened with the addition of value-added features such as FM, MP3 player, slider, torch, longer battery life and mobile tracker, Dutt said. The 11 models in the Guru series are priced between Rs 1,600 and Rs 3,500.         
	Samsung, which has a distribution tie-up with Iffco, is looking at collaborating with microfinance companies and self-help groups.        
	The Korean handset manufacturer will launch nine models in the high-end category this year with features such as touch-screen, multimedia and dual SIM cards.         
	US-based mobile maker Motorola also hopes to revive sales by focusing on smartphones, music phones and the (budget phone) Yuva series.        
	We are rolling out three new products. This includes phones with WiFi, 32-GB memory capacity, 5 megapixel camera, touch screen and based on Windows Mobile operating system, said Faisal Siddiqui, mobile devices head (India operations), Motorola.                                                                                                                                                           
